{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502700"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:48:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1890"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1890"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.11,0.12,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1890"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74542"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43986"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents for a routine health check. As he looks straight at the medical practitioner, the following sign is noted (Image 1). The doctor asks the patient to look sharply to the right. He does so and the patient says his eye \u0027has always been like that\u0027 (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to be malfunctioning?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left medial rectus","Right medial rectus","Left lateral rectus","Right lateral rectus","Right inferior oblique"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is unable to fully adduct his left eye. This is more clearly seen when the patient is asked to look directly ahead and the eyes rest. Adduction of the eyes is under the control of the oculomotor nerve. This cranial nerve (III) controls the medial rectus, inferior oblique, superior rectus and inferior rectus. The superior oblique is innervated by the trochlear nerve (IV) and the lateral rectus by the abducens (VI). He has a longstanding divergent squint (rather than a left partial third nerve palsy) and has a \u003Cstrong\u003Eweak medial rectus\u003C/strong\u003E and much stronger lateral rectus muscle. His left eye is amblyopic (ie poor vision) and he does not see double. The underlying cause is either a congenital or early developmental divergent squint which then results in left amblyopia (the brain, in effect, ignores or suppresses the image from the left eye).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve (III) controls the medial rectus, inferior oblique, superior rectus and inferior rectus. The superior oblique is innervated by the trochlear nerve (IV) and the lateral rectus by the abducens (VI)."],"references":["Mattos JL, Colman KL. Casselbrant ML, et al. Intratemporal and intracranial complications of acute otitis media in a pediatric population. Int J Pediatr Otorhinolaryngol. 2014; 78:2161-64."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74542"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1890"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19403"},{"type":"media","id":"19404"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19403"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://